” @", "score": 0.7913865, "raw_content": null}, {"url": "https://explainx.ai/blog/loop-engineering-coding-agents-claude-code-guide-2026", "title": "How to Design Coding Agent Loops That Run While You Sleep ...", "content": "# Loop Engineering: How to Design Coding Agent Loops That Run While You Sleep (2026 Guide). Loop engineering: write programs that prompt coding agents on cron, with guardrails and skills inside. From ReAct and ralph to /goal and /loop in Claude Code. **Loop engineering** is the shift from typing prompts into a coding agent to **writing the program that prompts the agent for you**. This guide exists because of one tweet—and the thousand replies asking what it actually meant. the other half is putting something in the loop that can say no: a test, a type check, a real error. Steinberger agreed—and pointed to **`VISION.md`**, a file he uses at the project level to anchor what agents should build toward (alongside agent rules in `AGENTS.md` and his broader agentic engineering workflow). **This post is the technical answer to \"how do we do that though?\"** — what a loop is, where it came from, how to build one, and what production teams worry about once the tweet wears off.", "score": 0.78334314, "raw_content": "[![](/skill-icon.svg)explainx.ai](/)[newsletter3.4k](https://newsletter.explainx.ai/?utm_source=explainx.ai&utm_medium=navbar&utm_campaign=newsletter \"Newsletter — about 3.4k readers\")\n\n[learn skills & mcp](https://www.udemy.com/course/agent-skills-claude-code-cursor-and-mcp-in-practice/?referralCode=5F72C84A71374224CEDE)\n\n[← Back to blog](/blog)\n\n\nexplainx / blog\n\n# Loop Engineering: How to Design Coding Agent Loops That Run While You Sleep (2026 Guide)\n\nLoop engineering: write programs that prompt coding agents on cron, with guardrails and skills inside. From ReAct and ralph to /goal and /loop in Claude Code.\n\n·15 min read·[Yash Thakker](/authors/yash-thakker)\n\nLoop EngineeringClaude CodeAI CodingAgent HarnessDeveloper Productivity\n\n**Loop engineering** is the shift from typing prompts into a coding agent to **writing the program that prompts the agent for you**. This guide exists because of one tweet—and the thousand replies asking what it actually meant.\n\n---\n\n## The tweet that triggered it\n\nOn **June 8, 2026 at 12:28 AM**, [Peter Steinberger (@steipete)](https://x.com/steipete?ref=explainx)—creator of [OpenClaw](https://openclaw.ai/?ref=explainx), now at OpenAI—posted two sentences that hit **6.5 million views** on X:\n\n> Here's your monthly reminder that you shouldn't be prompting coding agents anymore.\n>\n> You should be designing loops that prompt your agents.\n\nThat was it. No diagram. No repo link. The entire AI-coding timeline spent the next week arguing about six words.\n\n### What the replies actually asked\n\nThe thread surfaced three recurring questions:\n\n| Reply | Who | What they wanted |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| *\"Can you explain your workflow in detail? Would love a blog post about it\"* | [@MatthewBerman](https://x.com/MatthewBerman?ref=explainx) | A concrete how-to |\n| *\"how do we do that though?\"* | [@InderosD](https://x.com/InderosD?ref=explainx) | The on-ramp |\n| *\"wtf is a loop?\"* | [@MatthewBerman](https://x.com/MatthewBerman?ref=explainx) — [video explainer](https://x.com/MatthewBerman?ref=explainx) | A definition |\n\nBerman's early reply captured the mood before the explainers landed: *\"nobody knows but him and boris.\"*\n\nThe most useful reply in the thread came from [@mosyaseen](https://x.com/mosyaseen?ref=explainx):\n\n> \"designing the loop is half of it. the other half is putting something in the loop that can say no: a test, a type check, a real error. a loop with nothing to push back is the agent agreeing with itself on repeat.\"\n\nSteinberger agreed—and pointed to **`VISION.md`**, a file he uses at the project level to anchor what agents should build toward (alongside agent rules in [`AGENTS.md`](https://github.com/steipete/agent-scripts?ref=explainx) and his broader [agentic engineering workflow](https://steipete.me/posts/just-talk-to-it?ref=explainx)).\n\nSkeptics pushed back too: [@SaidAitmbarek](https://x.com/SaidAitmbarek?ref=explainx) flagged token efficiency; [@jxnlco](https://x.com/jxnlco?ref=explainx) noted Steinberger's outsized reach on the topic. Fair—but the question underneath was real: **if prompting is the old job, what is the new one?**\n\n[Matt Van Horn (@mvanhorn)](https://x.com/mvanhorn?ref=explainx)—who runs loops that open PRs across ~30 open-source repos overnight—ran `/last30days` research across Reddit, X, YouTube, and Hacker News and published a synthesis thread. [Boris Cherny](https://x.com/bcherny?ref=explainx) had already named the answer on stage four days earlier.\n\n**This post is the technical answer to \"how do we do that though?\"** — what a loop is, where it came from, how to build one, and what production teams worry about once the tweet wears off.\n\n**TL;DR**\n\n| Question | Answer |\n| --- | --- |\n| **What triggered this?** | [@steipete's June 8 tweet](https://x.com/steipete?ref=explainx) — 6.5M views, two sentences, one argument. |\n| **What is a loop?** | A program that prompts an agent, reads output, checks if done, repeats—or stops. |\n| **Who defines it cleanly?** | [Boris Cherny](https://x.com/bcherny?ref=explainx), Claude Code creator, at [WorkOS Acquired Unplugged (June 2, 2026)](https://workos.com/blog/acquired-unplugged-boris-cherny?ref=explainx). |\n| **Fastest on-ramp?** | Claude Code [`/loop`](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks?ref=explainx) — one slash command. |\n| **Old hat vs new?** | Single-agent **ralph** loops (2025) are baseline; **multi-agent orchestration** loops (2026) are the new layer. |\n| **What makes loops trustworthy?** | Self-verification: write → run → read result → correct. |\n| **What makes loops expensive?** | Not tokens per call—the **loop management** and runaway iterations. |\n\nLearn more about loop engineering\n\n \n\n---\n\n## The job moved up one altitude\n\n[Boris Cherny](https://x.com/bcherny?ref=explainx) created **Claude Code** as a side project in **September 2024**. It now sits behind close to **4% of all public commits on GitHub**, per industry reporting cited in the June 2026 discourse.\n\nAt **WorkOS Acquired Unplugged on June 2, 2026**, Boris gave the cleanest definition of what practitioners mean by \"loop\":\n\n> \"Now it's actually leveled up, I think, again, to the next wave of abstraction where I don't prompt Claude anymore. I have loops that are running. They're the ones that are prompting Claude and figuring out what to do. My job is to write loops.\"\n\nPlain version:\n\n1. You write a **small program** (or configure `/loop`).\n2. Each tick, it **prompts the coding agent**.\n3. It **reads what the agent produced** (files, test output, PR state).\n4. It **decides whether the task is done**.\n5. If not, it **prompts again**—with fresh or anchored context.\n\nYou stop being the thing inside the loop typing prompts. You become the **author of the loop**. The model becomes a **subroutine**.\n\nBoris describes three stages on his ladder:\n\n| Stage | What Boris did | Your role |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **1. Autocomplete** | Wrote code by hand with AI suggestions | Typist |\n| **2. Parallel sessions** | Ran 5–10 Claude sessions, prompted each | Prompt operator |\n| **3. Loops** | Writes loops; agents read GitHub, Slack, Twitter and decide what to build | Loop engineer |\n\nThe receipt: in the **30 days before December 27, 2025**, Boris reported that **100% of his contributions to Claude Code were written by Claude Code**—**259 PRs landed**. He deleted his IDE in **November 2025** and has not opened it since.\n\nThe nuance the \"prompt engineering is dead\" crowd skips: Boris is **not** saying engineers are obsolete. Someone still decides what to build, talks to customers, and coordinates teams. The job did not vanish—it moved from **writing code** to **writing the thing that writes the code**.\n\nFor the broader Anthropic framing, see our [harness engineering deep dive](/blog/anthropic-engineer-loops-prompts-ai-coding-harness-engineering-2026). This post focuses on **loop engineering as a buildable discipline**.\n\n[Live Bootcamp6 weeks\n\nComplete AI Builder Bootcamp\n\nClaude, Python automation & full-stack — 12 live sessions with Yash Thakker.\n\nView bootcamp→\n\nThe Complete AI Builder Bootcamp is the best AI development course for learning Claude AI, prompt engineering, Python automation, and full-stack web development. This intensive 6-week live bootcamp teaches you how to build AI-powered applications using Claude Projects, Claude Artifacts, Claude Code, and the complete Claude ecosystem. You'll master prompt engineering techniques, learn to create custom Claude connectors and MCP integrations, build Python automation workflows, develop full-stack websites with AI assistance, and create AI marketing agents.\n\nThe bootcamp includes 12 live Zoom sessions with Yash Thakker, founder of AISOLO Technologies and instructor to 350,000+ students. You'll build 8+ portfolio projects including AI playbooks, full-stack note-taking applications, Python automation scripts, marketing agents, and personal portfolio websites. The curriculum covers AI fundamentals, Claude Projects and Artifacts, Claude Co-work, Claude plugins and skills, Claude Code for Python development, full-stack development, AI marketing, and capstone projects.\n\nStudents receive 1-year access to all recordings, permanent Discord community access, a certificate of completion, and personalized career guidance. All enrollments include a 7-day money-back guarantee. This is the most comprehensive Claude AI bootcamp available, taking students from zero AI knowledge to expert AI builder in 6 weeks.](/bootcamps/complete-ai-builder-bootcamp) \n\n---\n\n## Why \"loop\" started five different arguments\n\nThe June 2026 replies were a mess because **\"loop\" hides at least five different things**. Here is the ladder—oldest to newest—so you can stop talking past people.\n\n### Stage 1: The academic while-loop (ReAct, 2022)\n\nThe [ReAct paper (2022)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629?ref=explainx) formalized the pattern: the model **reasons**, **calls a tool**, **reads the result**, **repeats** until done. One model, one loop, a human watching.\n\n### Stage 2: Goal-driven self-prompting (AutoGPT, 2023)\n\n**AutoGPT** gave an agent a goal and let it prompt itself. It became famous for **spinning forever doing nothing**—which seeded years of \"agents are a toy\" skepticism.\n\n### Stage 3: The ralph loop (July 2025)\n\n[Geoffrey Huntley](https://ghuntley.com/ralph/?ref=explainx) published the **ralph loop** in **July 2025**. In Huntley's words: **\"Ralph is a bash loop.\"**\n\n```\nwhile do cat done\n```\n\nThe innovation was not clever orchestration—it was **discipline**:\n\n* Every iteration **resets context** to a fixed set of anchor files (`PROMPT.md`, specs, `AGENTS.md`).\n* Progress lives on **disk and in git**, not in a growing conversation.\n* The agent does **one discrete unit of work** per iteration, validates, exits.\n\nHuntley used ralph to build **Cursed**, an esoteric programming language, for roughly **$297** in API costs—a number widely cited in practitioner threads. [Matt Pocock's workshop coverage](/blog/matt-pocock-ai-coding-real-engineers-workshop-2026) walks through a production-oriented ralph variant with test gates and commit-on-green logic.\n\n[@trashpandaemoji](https://x.com/trashpandaemoji?ref=explainx) had the sharpest reply under Steinberger's tweet:\n\n> \"It's not ralph/goal loops, that's old hat by now. It's probably some kind of continuous orchestration loop that oversees other threads/agents.\"\n\nThat reply is the closest correct answer in the public thread. Hold onto it.\n\n### Stage 4: Productized ralph (/goal, spring 2026)\n\nIn **spring 2026**, both **Codex** and **Claude Code** shipped a **`/goal` command** that runs until a validator confirms the task is done. See our [Claude Code /goal guide](/blog/claude-code-goal-command-long-running-agents-2026) and [Goal Mode complete guide](/blog/goal-mode-ai-agents-complete-guide-2026).\n\n### Stage 5: Orchestration loops (2026)\n\nWhat Boris and Steinberger actually mean in **June 2026** is genuinely new—not just renamed ralph. Four things changed:\n\n| Shift | Ralph (2025) | Orchestration loop (2026) |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **Unit of work** | One task, one agent | Loop supervises many tasks/agents |\n| **Concurrency** | Sequential bash pipe | Parallel sub-agents (worktrees, `/batch`) |\n| **Scheduling** | Human starts terminal | Cron, `/loop`, infrastructure time |\n| **Durability** | Terminal must stay open | Git-backed state, crash recovery |\n\n**Steve Yegge's [Gas Town](https://github.com/gastownhall/gastown?ref=explainx)** (launched **January 2026**) coordinates **20–30 Claude Code instances** via a \"Mayor\" agent, with patrol agents running continuous loops and state stored in git so work survives a crash. That is the **continuous orchestration loop** Trash Panda was reaching for—shipped and open source.\n\n---\n\n## \"It's just a cron job with a hat on\"\n\nThe best skeptic line in the June 2026 corpus was four words:\n\n> \"Cronjobs have funny re-branding rn.\"\n\n**Half right.** Yes—the scheduling layer is cron. Boris literally runs loops on cron. Claude Code's [`/loop` command](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks?ref=explainx) uses scheduling under the hood.\n\nIf your whole definition is *\"a thing that runs on a timer,\"* we invented that in **1975** and you can go home.\n\nWhat cron **never** had is the part in the middle:\n\n| Cron job | Agent loop |\n| --- | --- |\n| Runs a **fixed script** | Runs a **model** that reads current state |\n| Same branches every tick | **Decides** the next action each tick |\n| No self-correction | Can **verify, fail, and retry** |\n| One process | Can **dispatch and supervise** other agents |\n\n[@rohit\\_jsfreaky](https://x.com/rohit_jsfreaky?ref=explainx) deflated the mythology cleanly:\n\n> \"Every ai agent i shipped this year is a for-loop, an llm call, and a try/catch around the json parsing. The only thing agentic about it is the anthropic bill at the end of the month.\"\n\nHonest framing: **loops are cron plus a decision-maker in the body**. The interesting engineering is everything you wrap around that decision so it does not run off a cliff.\n\n---\n\n## What loop engineering looks like in practice\n\nEnough lineage. Here is the on-ramp.\n\n### One line: Claude Code `/loop`\n\nClaude Code ships `/loop` as a [bundled skill](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/skills?ref=explainx). Boris's canonical starter:\n\n```\n/loop babysit all my PRs. Auto-fix build issues, and when comments come in, use a worktree agent to fix them. \n```\n\nRead that twice. He is not asking Claude to fix **one PR**. He is asking Claude to **maintain all of them indefinitely**, dispatching worktree-isolated sub-agents as comments arrive.\n\nMore examples from Boris's public posts:\n\n| Command | What it does |\n| --- | --- |\n| `/loop 5m /babysit` | Auto-address code review, rebase PRs every 5 minutes |\n| `/loop 30m /slack-feedback` | Put up PRs for Slack feedback on a 30-minute cadence |\n| `/loop 5m check the deploy` | Poll deploy status on a fixed interval |\n| `/loop check the deploy` | Same prompt, interval chosen dynamically by Claude |\n\n**Dynamic intervals:** when you omit the interval, Claude picks a delay between **one minute and one hour** based on what it observed—short waits while a build is finishing, longer waits when nothing is pending.\n\n**Custom default:** a `loop.md` file in your project replaces the built-in maintenance prompt for bare `/loop`.\n\n**Stop a loop:** press **Esc** while it is waiting for the next iteration.\n\nSources: [Claude Code scheduled tasks docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks?ref=explainx), [Vibe Coder breakdown of /loop](https://blog.vibecoder.me/loops-stop-hooks-scheduled-agents-claude-code?ref=explainx).\n\n### Boris's five tips for hours-long autonomy\n\nIn **June 2026**, Boris posted five tips for running Opus autonomously for hours or days:\n\n1. **Auto mode for permissions** — Claude does not stop to ask for approval on every file write.\n2. **Dynamic workflows** — orchestrate hundreds or thousands of sub-agents for large tasks. See [Claude Code dynamic workflows](/blog/claude-code-dynamic-workflows-2026).\n3. **`/goal` or `/loop`** — nudge Claude to keep going until done.\n4. **Claude Code in the cloud** — close your laptop; the loop keeps running.\n5. **Self-verify end to end** — a loop is only as trustworthy as its ability to check its own work.\n\nTip **5** is what practitioners obsess over and hype skips.\n\n### The loop contract\n\n[Developers Digest](https://www.developersdigest.tech/blog/codex-loops-boris-cherny-agent-routines?ref=explainx) names the pieces that turn an agent from a clever assistant into a useful background process:\n\n```\nTRIGGER → every 15m, on PR comment, on CI failure SCOPE → open PRs authored by me, repo X only ACTION → run tests, fix lint, respond to review BUDGET → max 3 sub-agents per tick, 50k tokens STOP → all PRs green, or 10 iterations, or $5 spent REPORT → post summary to Slack #eng-bots \n```\n\nThat is not \"task, repeated.\" That is **loop engineering**.\n\n---\n\n## Verification: the feedback inside the loop\n\nThe fastest-growing sub-theme after Steinberger's tweet was not orchestration—it was **verification**. [@mosyaseen](https://x.com/mosyaseen?ref=explainx) said it directly in the thread: half of loop engineering is design; the other half is **something that can say no**.\n\n[@DanKornas](https://x.com/DanKornas?ref=explainx), shipping [roborev](https://github.com/roborev-dev/roborev?ref=explainx), put it plainly:\n\n> \"Your coding agent can move fast, but bad commits compound fast too.\"\n\nAn **open loop that writes code with no feedback** is a machine for generating confident mistakes. A loop that **writes → runs → reads the result → corrects** is what actually works in production.\n\n| Loop type | Behavior | Production fit |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **Open loop** | Agent writes until it says \"done\" | Demo only |\n| **Closed loop** | Agent runs tests/lint/review after each write | Ship with guardrails |\n| **Review loop** | Background reviewer feeds findings back while context is fresh | Best for long sessions |\n\nThe loop is not the magic. **The feedback inside it is.**\n\n### Anchor files: VISION.md, CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md\n\nSteinberger's reply in the thread pointed at **`VISION.md`**—a project-level file that states what you are building and why, so each loop tick does not re-derive intent from scratch. That sits alongside:\n\n| File | Role in loops |\n| --- | --- |\n| **`VISION.md`** | North star: product direction, constraints, what \"done\" looks like |\n| **`CLAUDE.md`** / **`AGENTS.md`** | Operating rules: stack, commands, guardrails per tick |\n| **`PROMPT.md`** / **`loop.md`** | The prompt the loop pipes in each iteration |\n| **Tests & type checks** | The thing that says **no** when the agent is wrong |\n\nPair loops with persistent project memory: [What is CLAUDE.md?](/blog/what-is-claude-md-persistent-memory-claude-code) and [MEMORY.md patterns](/blog/what-is-memory-md-ai-agent-persistence). Steinberger's shared agent rules live in [`steipete/agent-scripts`](https://github.com/steipete/agent-scripts?ref=explainx).\n\n---\n\n## Guardrails: the expensive part is managing the loop\n\nOnce the model writes code for almost nothing, cost moves to **the loop running it**.\n\n[@runes\\_leo](https://x.com/runes_leo?ref=explainx):\n\n> \"The costliest thing in AI coding is no longer writing code, it's managing the agent loop.\"\n\nThe receipt: **Uber capped engineers at $1,500 per person per tool per month** for Claude Code and Cursor after burning its annual AI budget in **four months**, per June 2026 reporting in the discourse.\n\n[@cv\\_usk](https://x.com/cv_usk?ref=explainx) on the failure mode everyone in production fears:\n\n> \"Without guardrails, you get infinite loops and billing surprises orders of magnitude over budget.\"\n\nEvery serious 2026 write-up converges on **three hard stops**:\n\n### 1. Maximum iteration count\n\n```\nwhile $iter $MAX_ITER do 1 done\n```\n\nClaude Code's `/goal` tracks **turns** natively. Bare ralph loops have no ceiling unless you add one.\n\n### 2. No-progress detection\n\nStop when the same error message, empty diff, or failing test appears **N times in a row**. Huntley tunes ralph prompts \"like a guitar\" based on failure patterns—loop engineering includes **prompt iteration**, not just bash.\n\n### 3. Token or dollar budget ceiling\n\nSet a per-loop budget before you sleep. [AI token cost governance](/blog/ai-token-costs-surge-enterprise-ramp-finance-governance) covers enterprise-scale patterns.\n\n**Gartner** puts agentic AI at the **peak of inflated expectations**, with only about **17% of organizations** actually deploying agents, per citations in Van Horn's research. The gap between the timeline and the receipts is the real state of play.\n\n---\n\n## Skills are the asset inside the loop\n\nSteinberger's other recurring point pairs with the loops thesis—and it is the more durable half:\n\n> If you do something more than once, turn it into an **automated skill**. If you do something hard, turn it into a skill afterward so next time is free.\n\nA loop with **no reusable skills** inside it is a `while true` around a stranger. A loop that calls a library of sharp, tested, named skills is a **system that compounds**.\n\nBoris's public advice: **experiment with turning workflows into skills + loops**.\n\n```\n/loop 30m /code-review /loop 15m /fix-ci /loop 1h /dependency-audit \n```\n\nEach skill is a **named recipe**—prompt + tool policy + verification steps. The loop is **plumbing** that invokes those recipes on a schedule.\n\nBrowse reusable skills at </skills>. For security before you automate: [Agent skills threat model](/blog/agent-skills-security-threat-explainx-verification).\n\n---\n\n## Build your first loop this week\n\n### Level 0: Babysit one PR (15 minutes)\n\n```\n/loop 10m Review PR #123. If CI is failing, fix it. If there are unresolved review comments, address them in a worktree and push. If everything is green and approved, stop. \n```\n\nWatch two ticks. Confirm it reads state before acting.\n\n### Level 1: Ralph with guardrails (1 hour)\n\nCreate `PROMPT.md`:\n\n```\n1.2.3. `npm test`4.5.6.\n```\n\nWrap it:\n\n```\n#!/bin/bash for in seq $MAX do cat \"BLOCKED\" break\"\\[ \\]\" break sleep done\n```\n\nRun in an isolated worktree or container—not on your main machine without sandboxing.\n\n### Level 2: Orchestration (ongoing)\n\nCombine `/loop` + skills + cloud sessions + `/goal` for multi-hour work. Read [agent harness engineering](/blog/agent-harness-engineering-terminal-bench-langchain-2026) for the seven-plane framework: loop policy, tool surface, context, sandbox, multi-agent routing, observability, model routing.\n\n---\n\n## Key patterns from the research\n\nSteinberger's tweet was the spark; the `/last30days` corpus (compiled **June 7–8, 2026**) distilled five durable patterns:\n\n1. **A loop is cron plus a decision-maker** — the model picks the next action each tick, not a hardcoded branch.\n2. **Lineage is real** — ReAct (2022) → AutoGPT (2023) → ralph (2025) → `/goal` (spring 2026) → orchestration loops (now). Single-agent ralph is old hat; multi-agent supervision is the new layer.\n3. **Feedback makes loops trustworthy** — tests, type checks, review gates; a loop with nothing to push back is the agent agreeing with itself.\n4. **Cost shifted to loop management** — cap iterations, detect no-progress, set a dollar budget.\n5. **Skills compound; prompts burn** — loops that call sharp named skills get cheaper over time; loops that re-derive everything do not.\n\nTop voices in the corpus: [@steipete](https://x.com/steipete?ref=explainx) (trigger), [@bcherny](https://x.com/bcherny?ref=explainx) (definition), [@MatthewBerman](https://x.com/MatthewBerman?ref=explainx) (explainer video), [@mvanhorn](https://x.com/mvanhorn?ref=explainx) (research synthesis), [@mosyaseen](https://x.com/mosyaseen?ref=explainx) (verification framing).\n\n---\n\n## Related reading\n\n**ExplainX guides**\n\n* [Loop Engineering Goes Mainstream: June 2026 Discourse Decoded](/blog/loop-engineering-mainstream-ai-skill-june-2026)\n* [Anthropic engineer: harness engineering explained](/blog/anthropic-engineer-loops-prompts-ai-coding-harness-engineering-2026)\n* [Claude Code /goal command](/blog/claude-code-goal-command-long-running-agents-2026)\n* [Claude Code dynamic workflows](/blog/claude-code-dynamic-workflows-2026)\n* [Matt Pocock: ralph loop in practice](/blog/matt-pocock-ai-coding-real-engineers-workshop-2026)\n* [Agent harness engineering: seven planes](/blog/agent-harness-engineering-terminal-bench-langchain-2026)\n\n**Primary sources**\n\n* [Claude Code: Run prompts on a schedule (`/loop`)](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/scheduled-tasks?ref=explainx)\n* [Claude Code: Bundled skills including `/loop`](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/skills?ref=explainx)\n* [Geoffrey Huntley: Ralph Wiggum loop (July 2025)](https://ghuntley.com/ralph/?ref=explainx)\n* [HumanLayer: Brief history of ralph](https://www.humanlayer.dev/blog/brief-history-of-ralph?ref=explainx)\n* [Gas Town (Steve Yegge)](https://github.com/gastownhall/gastown?ref=explainx)\n* [ReAct paper (2022)](https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629?ref=explainx)\n\n**Community synthesis**\n\n* [Peter Steinberger: the June 8, 2026 loop tweet](https://x.com/steipete?ref=explainx) — 6.5M+ views; origin of the discourse\n* [Matthew Berman: \"wtf is a loop?\" explainer](https://x.com/MatthewBerman?ref=explainx) — video follow-up to the thread\n* [Matt Van Horn: WTF Is a Loop? research thread](https://x.com/mvanhorn?ref=explainx) — `/last30days` across Reddit, X, YouTube, TikTok, HN, and GitHub\n* [Peter Steinberger: Just Talk To It (agentic engineering workflow)](https://steipete.me/posts/just-talk-to-it?ref=explainx)\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nLoop engineering is not a hot take about prompt engineering dying. It started as **two sentences from @steipete** and became a buildable discipline:\n\n1. **Stop being the thing in the loop** — write the loop once.\n2. **Anchor intent** — `VISION.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, or `AGENTS.md` so each tick knows where it's going.\n3. **Give it something that says no** — tests, type checks, review gates.\n4. **Give it skills worth calling** — named recipes, not one-off prompts.\n5. **Cap it so it halts** — iterations, no-progress detection, dollar budget.\n6. **Let it run on cron** while you decide what to build next.\n\nSteinberger named the shift; Boris shipped the primitives. The on-ramp, as of **June 2026**, is a single slash command:\n\n```\n/loop babysit all my PRs. Auto-fix build issues, and when comments come in, use a worktree agent to fix them. \n```\n\nThe only people who truly know what a loop feels like are the ones who have already built one. [@InderosD](https://x.com/InderosD?ref=explainx) asked *\"how do we do that though?\"* in the original thread—the sections above are the answer. The good news: the tooling to start is already in your terminal.\n\n---\n\n*Published June 9, 2026. Steinberger tweet view count and thread citations from June 8–9, 2026—verify against upstream before citing in production decisions.*\n\n## Related posts\n\n[Jun 8, 2026\n\n### Anthropic Engineer: Stop Prompting Claude, Build Loops That Prompt Themselves (Harness Engineering Explained)\n\nSingle prompts are dead for serious software development. Anthropic engineers run iterative loops where Claude observes, plans, acts, and reflects over hours or days, shipping 8x more code with 80%+ authored by AI by May 2026.](/blog/anthropic-engineer-loops-prompts-ai-coding-harness-engineering-2026)[Jun 17, 2026\n\n### What Is Self-Harness? The AI Agent Pattern That Improves Its Own Scaffolding\n\nA harness wraps your AI model. A self-harness lets the model improve that wrapper on its own. Here is how the weakness-mining, proposal, and validation loop works — and why it consistently produces 15–52% benchmark gains without touching the base model.](/blog/what-is-self-harness-ai-agents-complete-guide-2026)[Jun 16, 2026\n\n### Loop Engineering Is Now the Most-Discussed AI Skill on Developer Twitter\n\nOne week ago \"loop engineering\" was a term most developers hadn't heard. Today it is trending across X with 2,200+ posts, championed by Anthropic's Boris Cherny and OpenAI's Peter Steinberger, critiqued by Matt Pocock, and joked about by everyone who has watched Claude say \"You're right to push back! I over-engineered this!\" 87 times in a row. Here is the full picture.](/blog/loop-engineering-mainstream-ai-skill-june-2026)"}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/posts/ashish-chaudhary-001a9a47_a-tweet-from-peter-steinberger-crossed-8-activity-7470621101258129409-ikWR", "title": "Design Loops for AI to Scale, Not Prompt | Ashish Chaudhary posted on the topic | LinkedIn", "content": "A tweet from Peter Steinberger crossed 8 million views this week. The idea is simple. Stop prompting your coding agents. Start designing", "score": 0.7817479, "raw_content": "## LinkedIn respects your privacy\n\nLinkedIn and 3rd parties use essential and non-essential cookies to provide, secure, analyze and improve our Services, and to show you relevant ads (including **professional and job ads**) on and off LinkedIn. Learn more in our [Cookie Policy](https://www.linkedin.com/legal/cookie-policy).\n\nSelect Accept to consent or Reject to decline non-essential cookies for this use. You can update your choices at any time in your [settings](https://www.linkedin.com/mypreferences/g/guest-cookies).\n\nAgree & Join LinkedIn\n\nBy clicking Continue to join or sign in, you agree to LinkedIn’s [User Agreement](/legal/user-agreement?trk=linkedin-tc_auth-button_user-agreement), [Privacy Policy](/legal/privacy-policy?trk=linkedin-tc_auth-button_privacy-policy), and [Cookie Policy](/legal/cookie-policy?trk=linkedin-tc_auth-button_cookie-policy).\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n![]()\n\n# Design Loops for AI to Scale, Not Prompt\n\n![View profile for Ashish Chaudhary]()\n\nA tweet from Peter Steinberger crossed 8 million views this week. The idea is simple. Stop prompting your coding agents. Start designing loops that prompt your agents. It sounds like a developer tip. It is actually a description of where all of software is heading.\nFirst, what a loop actually is. Four steps that repeat. The agent looks at the current state. It decides the next action. It acts. Then it checks the result against the goal. If the goal is not met, it goes around again, now with new information. That is the whole thing. No magic. The intelligence is not in any single step. It comes from the repetition. Prompting, by contrast, is manual labor. You ask, the model answers, you check, you ask again. You are the loop. It works, but it scales to exactly one person and one screen.\nThe shift is to move yourself up a level. You stop writing the prompt and start designing the system that writes it. Your job becomes three things. The goal. The tools. And the test that tells the loop whether it is getting closer. That test is everything. A loop without a good test is automated guessing. A loop with one gets better every run, while you sleep.\nNow the warning, because this is where teams get burned.\nNever give a loop an open ended objective. \"Make the code better\" or \"keep improving until perfect\" is not a goal, it is a money printer running in reverse. The loop will happily think in circles, retry forever, and burn through tokens at a rate that turns your unit economics upside down.\nEvery loop needs four guardrails. A precise, checkable goal. A token and iteration budget. A stop condition. And a clean handoff to a human when it stalls.\nThe new skill is not prompt writing. It is loop design. The engineers who get this are not using AI. They are managing it. Different job, and the one worth learning now.\n\n![graphical user interface, text, application, chat or text message]()\n\n\n![]()\n![]()\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n![Sivamani Battala, graphic]()\n\nThe idea that the test is everything feels underappreciated. Most discussions focus on prompts, agents, or guardrails, but the harder question seems to be how teams define success before the loop runs. Who usually owns that decision in practice, engineering, product, or someone else?\n\n![Vivek Chand, graphic]()\n\nA easier approach to adopt in your existing project is with [FLYWHEEL.md](http://FLYWHEEL.md?trk=public_post_comment-text) - a single file explaining the loop\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Elinkedin%2Ecom%2Fposts%2Fashish-chaudhary-001a9a47_a-tweet-from-peter-steinberger-crossed-8-activity-7470621101258129409-ikWR&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n## More Relevant Posts\n\n![View organization page for roadmap.sh]()\n\n8,757 followers\n\nSergio's post names something we see in our data but rarely hear said this clearly.\nMost developers (including the team at [roadmap.sh](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=http%3A%2F%2Froadmap%2Esh&urlhash=-hdD&trk=public_post-text)) are learning AI tools right now are doing it without much structure. Experimenting, breaking things, building intuitions in isolation. The roadmap doesn't replace that process. It reflects it back at you and shows you the gaps you didn't know existed.\nThat's the difference between a checklist and a mental map. One tells you what to do. The other tells you where you are.\nHow people use AI tools is rapidly changing as agents get better and new features are added. We're working to keep the AI-related roadmaps up-to-date and relevant for newcomers, but also people who are already using AI in their daily routines. If you're in that position and haven't looked at them yet, they're worth a look.\nCheck the full roadmap catalog: 👇\n[https://lnkd.in/e\\_bSYUF](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2Fe_bSYUF&urlhash=hF_c&trk=public_post-text)\n\n![View profile for Sergio Fernández García]()\n\nBusiness Intelligence Analyst | Big Data & Data Analytics\n\nI've been messing around with Claude Code for a couple of months. Often with no order or guidance... trying things, breaking others, learning by trial and error.\nRecently I came across two roadmaps from [roadmap.sh](https://www.linkedin.com/company/roadmapsh?trk=public_post_reshare-text): \"Claude Code\" and \"AI Agents\". And I wish I'd seen them earlier. Not to follow them as a checklist, but as a mental map: they've helped me solidify what I was already doing, confirm half-formed intuitions, and learn pieces I didn't even know I was missing.\nWhat I'm applying today: Claude Code in my daily work — context via [CLAUDE.md](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=http%3A%2F%2FCLAUDE%2Emd&urlhash=onXc&trk=public_post_reshare-text), skills, MCP to connect my actual systems. That already delivers results.\nThe next step I want to explore: moving from \"an agent that does tasks\" to an agent architecture. Specialists that own one specific task, and an orchestrator that decides who to delegate to and how to chain the work.\nI have no idea how all this will change in the short and medium term... the tools, the agents, how far it goes. But I do have a hunch: getting on board now, tinkering and learning, will make the difference versus whoever controls little or nothing. I see it as an investment.\nAnd we'll see if, half-joking, half-serious, ten years from now compound interest applies here too. 😄\nIf you haven't come across them, take a look at these roadmaps on [roadmap.sh](https://www.linkedin.com/company/roadmapsh?trk=public_post_reshare-text) — a solid base to get started, in my opinion.\n\n\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Froadmapsh_roadmaps-claude-code-ai-agents-activity-7462411561689640965-lXFe&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Prad Mandal]()\n\nIf your Claude Code usage disappears after one prompt, you’re probably using it wrong.\nMeanwhile, I’ve used it for 10–12 hour working days, across fairly large codebases and still haven’t burned through my limits. Most weeks, I’m nowhere close to using my full allowance — and no, I’m not on the 20x plan.\nThe difference is workflow.\nYou can’t dump a vague idea into AI, ask it to build the whole product in one shot, and expect clean results.\nYou need proper setup, clear context, smaller tasks, guardrails, reviews, and planning before coding.\nClaude Code is not as intimidating as people think.\nYou need a system.\nSo I made a practical guide on how I set up Claude Code for projects.\nThis first version covers the setup, structure, do’s and don’ts, usage-saving habits, and the workflow I use to avoid wasting prompts and context.\nMy suggestion: read it once, then feed it into Claude Code when starting a new project so it can help create the right structure for what you’re building.\nComment “Guide” and I’ll send it over.\n\n![No alternative text description for this image]()\n\n\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fpradyut-mandal_if-your-claude-code-usage-disappears-after-activity-7467062375070797824-hb8U&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View organization page for AgileForce]()\n\n1,474 followers\n\nMost people still think software gets written line by line.\nThat version of reality disappeared quietly.\nA lot of developers today are doing something called vibe coding.\nHere is what it actually looks like:\nYou open Cursor and describe a feature in plain English.\n“Build me an authentication flow.”\nYou use Claude to debug logic or refactor messy code.\nYou let Copilot autocomplete repetitive tasks.\nSuddenly, what used to take days gets built in hours.\nIt sounds unreal. Because honestly, it kind of is.\nBut here is what people misunderstand:\nAI tools are brilliant at helping you write code.\nThey are not brilliant at deciding whether that code is actually safe to ship.\nThey do not truly understand:\n• whether your auth flow has gaps\n• if your database queries will collapse at scale\n• if your architecture will become painful in 3 months\n• what happens when real users behave unpredictably\nThe code works.\nUntil production reminds you that “working” and “production ready” are not the same thing.\nThat is where VibeCheck comes in.\nYou build with AI.\nSenior engineers review what AI cannot fully reason about:\nSecurity, performance, architecture and production readiness\nBecause vibe coding is powerful.\nBut blind speed is expensive.\n\n![No alternative text description for this image]()\n![]()\n\n\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fagileforceltd_most-people-still-think-software-gets-written-activity-7467964750216302593-xIP1&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Robert Reed]()\n\nSmall example of why I keep saying domain beats code.\nI’m working on a prompt refinement product.\nThe plan was simple:\nGive people 5 free uses, then move them to a paid tier.\nNothing complicated.\nBut then the maintenance manager side of my brain kicked in.\nI started thinking like I would at work:\nWhere does this fail?\nHow does someone misuse it?\nWhat happens when people do the thing they’re not supposed to do?\nIs the limit actually enforced, or does it just look enforced?\nSo I checked it before launch.\nFound a flaw.\nFixed it.\nThat’s it.\nNo dramatic hacker story.\nNo “I got attacked.”\nNo fake founder drama.\nJust a basic example of what real-world experience does.\nA coder can build what you asked for.\nAn operator asks what can go wrong after it’s built.\nThat difference matters.\nEspecially with AI tools.\nBecause right now everybody is talking about how fast they can build.\nBut fast doesn’t mean solid.\nFast doesn’t mean safe.\nFast doesn’t mean ready for customers.\nI’m learning that the value is not just in writing prompts or generating code.\nThe value is knowing what questions to ask before something breaks.\nThat comes from domain experience.\nThat comes from years of seeing systems fail in the real world.\nDomain beats code.\nI’m the proof of concept.\n\n\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Frobertreedai_small-example-of-why-i-keep-saying-domain-activity-7470811993742929920-xiCl&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Kristin Blumberg]()\n\nSpent some time with our new Cursor Insights report and there's one stat that really stands out:\nThe top 1% of developers are producing 46x more lines of code and merging 15x more PRs than the median 🤯\nIf you're running a large eng org, that's the number that should stop you. AI isn't lifting your whole team evenly. It's compounding for the people who already had taste, judgment, and pattern recognition. Your best engineers just got a lot more valuable, and most retention strategies haven't caught up.\nA few other findings worth flagging:\n💡 Agent-generated code reaching commit without a manual diff review jumped from 7% in January to ~36% in May. Five months. Trust is moving faster than most exec dashboards.\n💡 81% of accepted AI code is still in the codebase an hour later. So much for the \"AI just writes throwaway code\" objection.\n💡 Tool calls per agent session up 30% in the last two months alone. Agents are getting deeper, fast.\nThe exec takeaway shouldn't be \"buy more AI tools.\" It's that the gap between teams using them well and teams using them poorly is widening every quarter. The companies treating AI coding as infrastructure (not a perk for early adopters) are pulling away.\nFull report: [cursor.com/insights](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=http%3A%2F%2Fcursor%2Ecom%2Finsights&urlhash=i6uU&trk=public_post-text)\n\n![Cursor · The Cursor Developer Habits Report]()\n\n\n![]()\n![]()\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fkblumberg1_cursor-developer-habits-report-agentic-coding-activity-7465857243478020096-CIyk&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Evan Israel Brenner]()\n\nI've built real, working software this year. AI phone agents, websites, automations that run on their own.\nAnd I'm not really a coder.\nTen years ago that was a contradiction. Building meant knowing the languages, the syntax, the frameworks. If you couldn't write it, you couldn't make it. The code was the gate.\nThat gate is gone.\nThe skill now isn't coding. It's thinking clearly enough to describe what you actually want.\nAnd before that sounds easy, look closer. Most people can't do it. Ask someone what they want and you get fog. Vague in, vague out. The machine builds exactly what you describe, which means what you get is capped by the clarity of what you ask for.\nSo the bottleneck moved. It used to be technical. Now it's mental. The hard part isn't the building anymore. It's knowing, precisely, what you're trying to build.\nThat's the good news and the bad news. Good, because you don't need a computer science degree to make things now. Bad, because you can't hide behind not having one either.\nThe tools got easy. Knowing what you want is still the hard part.\nThe human part.\n\n\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fevanisraelbrenner_ive-built-real-working-software-this-year-activity-7468862912317640704-U7oi&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Pete Short]()\n\nIntroducing the Cursor Developer Habits Report.\nWe’re sharing some of our findings on how software development is changing. It’s based on the most comprehensive dataset on AI coding in the world, across all model families.\nFive themes emerged in our research:\n1. Developer acceleration\n2. The economics of intelligence\n3. The power user gap\n4. The rise of context, and\n5. The shift to automation.\nRead the full report here: [cursor.com/insights](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=http%3A%2F%2Fcursor%2Ecom%2Finsights&urlhash=i6uU&trk=public_post-text)\n\n![Cursor · The Cursor Developer Habits Report]()\n\n\n![]()\n![]()\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fpetershort_cursor-developer-habits-report-agentic-coding-activity-7465833899647049732-eHUs&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Mike Kinsella]()\n\nCursor's developer habits report dropped this week. Shameless plug: it's a fascinating read, but I'm thinking about one stat in it.\n[https://lnkd.in/gtrxTzuR](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FgtrxTzuR&urlhash=iR_h&trk=public_post-text)\nThe top 1% of developers using Cursor produce 46x more code than the median user. 15x more PRs merged. The Gini coefficient on AI-assisted output is 0.77 (raise your hand if you're like me and when you saw 'Gini coefficient' you pictured the guy from Aladdin running a hedge fund)\nI'm guilty of this, but when a vendor or analyst tells you \"developers got X% more productive with AI,\" that's not telling you everyone got X% better. It's telling you a small group got dramatically better, the middle moved a little, and some of your team didn't really change.\nFor VPs of Engineering, I think the right question here isn't \"how much lift are we getting?\" It's \"who are our P99 users, what are they actually doing differently, and how do we move the next decile of the team toward it.\"\nThis is where you focus to drive more of your team up the AI maturity curve. Tell me what you thought of when you read 'Gini coefficient' in the comments. 😜\n\n![Cursor Developer Habits Report: Agentic Coding Trends]()\n\n\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fmike-kinsella-158a9921_cursor-developer-habits-report-agentic-coding-activity-7470499212464570369-_NuF&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Yair Beer]()\n\nThree criticisms I hear constantly about LLMs in development. All valid. All solvable.\n\"I want to program, not babysit LLMs.\"\nSame argument people made against IDEs, linters, and autocomplete. Nobody writes production code in notepad anymore. LLMs are the next step in that same progression — fancier autocomplete with broader reach. The tool evolved. The craft didn't. Like any tool, the return depends on the developer wielding it.\n\"LLMs are stochastic and can't be trusted.\"\nAsk three engineers to implement the same feature, you get three different solutions. We aren't deterministic either. The actual gap: LLMs verify poorly. They generate confidently but don't catch their own mistakes. Tests solve this for both humans and models. Write the test first, let the model write the implementation, run it. That loop makes stochastic output reliable.\n\"LLMs don't learn from their mistakes.\"\nThey can, at three levels I use daily. User-level: when an error repeats, I add it to the model's memory in the general config as an explicit instruction or skill. Project-level: I maintain an [AGENTS.md](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=http%3A%2F%2FAGENTS%2Emd&urlhash=jh-H&trk=public_post-text) with guidelines, context, and conventions the model reads every session. Task-level: I carry a running summary between chats so context doesn't evaporate.\nToday this is mostly manual, Nous Research's Hermes ([https://lnkd.in/e4335Wcy](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2Fe4335Wcy&urlhash=kcfG&trk=public_post-text)) is working to automate that loop, but the burden still falls on you.\nEvery criticism here points at a real limitation. Dismiss LLMs over these defaults and you're walking away from serious leverage because the out-of-the-box experience isn't perfect.\nThe developers I see getting real value aren't writing better prompts. They built a better environment around the model.\nWhat's your biggest friction point when coding with LLMs, and have you tried solving it at the environment level rather than the prompt level?\n[#ArtificialIntelligence](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fartificialintelligence&trk=public_post-text) [#SoftwareEngineering](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fsoftwareengineering&trk=public_post-text) [#LLMs](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fllms&trk=public_post-text) [#GenerativeAI](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fgenerativeai&trk=public_post-text) [#DeveloperTools](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fdevelopertools&trk=public_post-text)\n\n![evolution of programming tools]()\n![]()\n\n\n![]()\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fyair-beer_artificialintelligence-softwareengineering-activity-7468190222720274433-r6q5&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Harisankar S]()\n\nThe Cursor Developer Habits Report just dropped — and the numbers tell a story that goes way beyond productivity.\nDevelopers went from writing ~3,600 lines/week in early 2025 to ~8,600 lines/week by May 2026.\nPRs aren't just bigger — they're fundamentally different. Average lines per PR jumped from 126 to 345. \"Mega PRs\" (1,000+ lines) now make up nearly 14% of all merged PRs.\nAnd the productivity gap? The top 1% of developers generate 46x more AI-assisted lines than the median. They merge 15x more PRs per week.\nBut here's what I think most people are missing:\nThis isn't just about speed. It's about a structural shift in what a software engineer actually does.\nThe role is quietly splitting into two tracks:\n→ Those who use AI as a faster keyboard\n→ Those who use AI as a multiplier on their thinking\nThe second group isn't just writing more code. They're designing systems, making architectural decisions, and guiding agents through complex, multi-step workflows. The craft is moving upstream.\nThat has real implications for teams:\n→ Code review processes built for 126-line PRs aren't ready for 345-line ones\n→ Engineering culture needs to define what \"good\" looks like when AI writes the first draft\n→ The skills that made someone a great IC two years ago aren't the same ones that make them great today\nThe question isn't whether AI will reshape software engineering. That's already happening.\nThe question is whether your team's workflows, norms, and culture are evolving fast enough to match it.\nRead more about the report -> [https://lnkd.in/gBiy3efn](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FgBiy3efn&urlhash=TJEU&trk=public_post-text)\n[#SoftwareEngineering](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fsoftwareengineering&trk=public_post-text) [#AI](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fai&trk=public_post-text) [#EngineeringLeadership](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fengineeringleadership&trk=public_post-text) [#AgenticAI](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fagenticai&trk=public_post-text) [#DeveloperTools](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fdevelopertools&trk=public_post-text)\n\n![Cursor Developer Habits Report: Agentic Coding Trends]()\n\n\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fharisankarsivankutty_cursor-developer-habits-report-agentic-coding-activity-7467579644003708928-L7HC&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![](https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D5616AQGkumrOvt-HQg/profile-displaybackgroundimage-shrink_200_800/profile-displaybackgroundimage-shrink_200_800/0/1715304952573?e=2147483647&v=beta&t=iwqSzoc7hk8H_v0V2Uoys6cZ7SVr3oTKLbEKDQw71Og)\n![Ashish Chaudhary]()\n\n5,594 followers\n\n## More from this author\n\n![]()\n\n### Hidden Cost of \"Cash\"...\n\n![]()\n\n### iPhone 6s and iPhone 6s Plus: What Apple changed?\n\n![]()\n\n### Microsoft Surface Pro 3 Vs Other Tablets\n\n## Explore content categories\n\n![]()\n\n## Sign in to view more content\n\nCreate your free account or sign in to continue your search\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nor\n\nNew to LinkedIn? [Join now](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Elinkedin%2Ecom%2Fposts%2Fashish-chaudhary-001a9a47_a-tweet-from-peter-steinberger-crossed-8-activity-7470621101258129409-ikWR&trk=public_post_contextual-sign-in-modal_join-link)\n\nBy clicking Continue to join or sign in, you agree to LinkedIn’s [User Agreement](/legal/user-agreement?trk=linkedin-tc_auth-button_user-agreement), [Privacy Policy](/legal/privacy-policy?trk=linkedin-tc_auth-button_privacy-policy), and [Cookie Policy](/legal/cookie-policy?trk=linkedin-tc_auth-button_cookie-policy).\n\nLinkedIn\n\nNever miss a beat on the app\n\nDon’t have the app? Get it in the Microsoft Store."}, {"url": "https://x.com/steipete/status/2063697162748260627", "title": "Here's your monthly reminder that you shouldn't be prompting ...", "content": "Here's your monthly reminder that you shouldn't be prompting coding agents anymore. You should be designing loops that prompt your agents.", "score": 0.72348577, "raw_content": null}], "response_time": 4.72, "request_id": "45ec2e88-66ed-469b-bd68-a7e3c7fffa66"}